Notes: Can't tell if there was an M3.
LNM2 occlusal lesion is on the hypoconid; it's possible it was formed secondary to a chip.
LNI2 is unerupted, which is a bit surprising.
Note labial wear of LNI1, LNI2, and LNC, indicating extramasticatory use of teeth.
Distal root of LNM1 has been destroyed by a carious lesion.

LNM1 has two buccal abscesses present, at the two buccal roots (beneath the protoconid and hypoconid).  It's unclear whether the lingual abscess goes with LNI1 or LNI2, but based on the wear, I assume it goes with LNI2.

LNM3 not congenitally absent because of presence of an IPCF on the LNM2.  LNM2 root was clearly diseased (buccally), but no clear abscess.  LNM1 appears to have both a root lesion (buccally) and an interproximal one.
Because of concretions, it's hard to tell if LNM1-LNI1 are missing or have fallen out antemortem.
LNM1 lesion is proximal.
Labial wear on both NP3s.
Possible congenital absence of M3 bilaterally.  Unclear if P4 was lost perimortem or postmortem.  M2 alv remodelled, M1 starting to remodel, P3 and C mostly remodelled, Is completely remodelled.
AMTL of both NM1s.
Discoloration of anterior teeth.  See photos.
Probable congenital absence of both NM3s, but unsure.
See photographs of hypoplasias.  LNM1 has definite enamel defects near the occlusal surface of the crown, as does RNM1.  LNP3 has an array of pits distally, but RNP3 is normal.
LNM3 is present in crypt.

All alveoli show evidence of resorption and shortening; it is unclear how many teeth were lost antemortem.  All teeth coded as 5 have open alveoli but significantly shortened or with evidence of remodelling (except LNI1, which is healed.)
Chipping on LNP3 appears curved and worn.
LNM1 could just be a pit, but it looks like a small occlusal carious lesion to me.  Single pit on the LNI1, probable hypoplasia.
NM3s are not in occlusion and can barely be seen through a hole in the alveolus.
Chip on LNM1 is the fifth cusp; most of it is chipped and obviously worn.
LNM3 lesion is large but obviously originated interproximally (mesial).  LNM2 lesion is distal.
LNM1 lesion is mesial, LNP4 is distal.
LNM1 might have two medium interproximal distal chips, but it's hard to tell if they're worn chips or just wear.  Not scored as chips.  NM3s are peg-shaped, almost like premolars.
Tooth roots remain in sockets, but crowns are broken, damaged, and crumble when you touch them.  All 8's indicate teeth present in roots but with unobservable crowns.
LNM1 carious lesion is inteproximal distal and large (5th cusp is gone).
NI1s are both broken mid-crown.
LNI1 has calculus all around the crown, including interproximally, but it is heaviest on the distal-lingual aspect.
LNIs also have a little lingual calculus, but there is more labial calculus.

Unsure if LNC is present in the mandibular bone or not.  I can see the RNC unerupted through the bone.  In place of LNC is the dLNC.  Molar wear totals are correct.  LNM1 is significantly less worn than LNM2 and LNM3.
LNIs can be barely seen through eruption openings in the mandible.
Possible congenital absence of M3s, but it is unclear.
Incisor could be a lateral, but based on wear and calculus formation, I'm fairly certain it's a central incisor.
LNM2 has an occlusal chip.
LNP4 is worn severely.  No enamel remains, and the wear is angled mesially-distally at about a 45 degree angle.  See photos.
LNIs are hidden in their crypts.
LNM3 possibly in the process of being lost - significant bone reaction and resorption around the roots.  LNP4 destroyed by caries, only roots remain.
Subadult, so no idea if there are M3 buds.
LNP4 is either missing or unerupted, as this individual has retained dLNM1 into adulthood.
Possible retention of dLNC into adulthood.  See photos.
